Task 1: The DAG

- Come up with an incredibly interesting and scientifically important made-up example for a phenomenon to investigate. Decide on two variables (an outcome and a predictor) that you would like to investigate the relation between. If in doubt, you can be inspired by Peter’s amazing example on the next page.

In our example, we wish to investigate the effect of the predictor corona fear (CF) on the outcome variable energy level (continuous)

Since Denmark reported it’s first case of COVID-19 contraction on the 27th February 2020 (STPS, 2020), COVID-19 and its development has been subject to extensive coverage in Danish media. News media has a critical role in times of epidemic crises since exposure to as well as consumption of information in times of pandemics may alter people’s perception and provoke behavioural changes that might ultimately impact the evolution and further spread of the virus (Gozzi et al., 2020).

We therefore expect that corona fear is a sensible predictor of whether one gets infected or not, assuming that the degree to which one fears COVID determines the precautions and actions one take to avoid getting infected.

Predictor: corona fear (continuous variable) Outcome variable: energy level (continuous variable), depends on germ level as germs gobble up nutrients and energy. Sanitizing: continuous variable (count variable) Social exposure: a measure of how much social mingling you engage in (social circle size, social activities etc.) Germ level: the level of vira germs in your body. We have no biological evidence for a variable of this type, but for the sake of simplicity we assumes that the level of germs present in your body can be describes as a normally distributed continuous variable

- Make a DAG for the phenomenon. Make it medium complicated: that means, make sure there are some different kinds of relations (see next step). Change it if you don’t get anything interesting for the next steps.
Draw it somehow (on paper, in R, laser engraved in diamond).
Code it in dagitty (this is a nice tool: http://dagitty.net/dags.html )

- Find elemental forms of variable relations in the DAG (i.e., forks, pipes, colliders, and their descendants).

Pipe

(FM -> GERM -> INFECTED)

(Cf –> FM –> GERM)

(CF -> S -> GERM)

(S –> GERM –> INFECTED)

Fork

(S <- CF -> FM)

Collider

(S -> GERM <- FM)

We inspect the variable FM to depend on your corona fear, as we assume that a person who is really scared of COVID would be much more likely to strictly follow the national guidelines, whereas a person who didn’t fear corona at all would reversely be much less likely to wear a face mask although the national guidelines advises one to do it

The same goes for the relation between corona fear and sanitising. We expect a person with a high corona fear to have a much higher daily frequency of sanitising than a person with no corona fear at all.

We would expect germ level to depend on whether you wear face mask when advised to or not, as the face mask (at least partly) prevents germs from entering your mouth and nose.

The same goes for the relation between germ level and sanitising, as sanitising works by killing most germs, preventing them from entering your body

Lastly, we expect the level of germs to determine whether you are infected or not. With a low level of germs, one would expect your immune system would be strong enough to fight the few germs that have entered your body. However, if the level of germs in your body is extremely high, it might exceed the capacity of your immune system to fight back, resulting in you getting infected.

You can ask your computer to reproduce this analysis, to analyze the graph and find the necessary variables to control for in order to block the backdoor. The dagitty R package provides adjustmentSets for this purpose

In order to shut the backdoor. Here’s the recipe: (1) List all of the paths connecting X (the potential cause of interest) and Y (the out- come). (2) Classify each path by whether i t is open or closed. A path is open unless it contains a collider. (3) Classify each path by whether it is a backdoor path. A backdoor path has an arrow entering X. (4) If there are any backdoor paths that are also open, decide which variable(s) to con- dition on to close it. Let’s consider some examples.

Task 4: Messing it up

- Try and deliberately have an open back door path and see if you can get wrong inference.

We now create a DAG that has the variable OCD as backdoor that directly influences both corona fear and sanitizing. We expect a person with severe OCD sanitize more often (independently of corona fear), but also to fear corona more, which then has a direct influence on sanitizing as well.

# Shutting the backdoor - analyzing the graph to block the backdoor
adjustmentSets(twisted_dag_corona, exposure="corona_fear", outcome="infected")

{ OCD }

Including OCD introduces an open backdoor path to infected. OCD is a confounded variable that may result in our model making wrong inferences. When introducing OCD in the DAG, OCD creates a confounding path going from OCD –> SAN –> GL –> INF. We want to block it in order to avoid any spurious correlation that prevents us from seeing the actual effect that corona_fear has on infection.

The path CF <- OCD -> sanitizing is a backdoor path because it enters corona fear with an arrow and also connects corona fear to sanitizing. This path is confounding.We can deconfound this model by stratifying by OCD. Since sanitizing and corona fear in the above dag share the common cause, OCD, we can separate them statistically by stratifying by their common cause, OCD.

OBS: JØRGEN. In this case, controlling for OCD ruins inference as it does not belong to the causal path from corona fear to corona infected. Why? Because if only the 2 path (as descibed above) existed and we decided to change CF it wouldn’t affect INF. To account for this, we could isolate OCD (the confounder) by adding it to the model by conditioning on it. When conditioning, we’re analyzing the values of the other variables for a given value of the conditioned variable. This would block the second path and thus allow for inclusion of OCD in the model.

Peter’s perfectly optimal and extremely interesting example

In a galaxy far, far away…

It is a period of civil wars in the galaxy. A brave alliance of underground freedom fighters has challenged the tyranny and oppression of the awesome GALACTIC EMPIRE.

To crush the rebellion once and for all, the EMPIRE is constructing a sinister new battle station. Powerful enough to destroy an entire planet, its completion spells certain doom for the champions of freedom.

The evil Emperor has figured out, however, that neither the battle station nor the Force can help him avoid that more solar systems join the rebellion. He has therefore hired a CogSci student to use causal modelling and multiple linear regressions to investigate how the activity of the Death Star and other factors affects the probability that a given solar system will join the rebellion (this allows him to more optimally suppress freedom in the Galaxy).

You are that student.

We assume that the probability of a solar system joining the rebellion depends on
- how many rebellion sympathizers there is in the system (more rebels -> higher probability of joining the rebellion)
- how scared people are in the system (more scared -> lower probability of joining the rebellion).

How many rebellion sympathizers there is in a system depends on

- crime levels (less crime -> less rebellion sympathizers)

- number of planets recently destroyed by the Death Star (more planets destroyed -> more rebellion sympathizers)

- number of Jedis in the system (more Jedis -> more rebellion sympathizers)

How scared people are depends on

- whether or not the Death Star is nearby (nearby -> more scared)

- how many jedis are in the system (more Jedis -> less scared)

- how much time Darth Vader has spent in the system recently (more time -> more scared)

Crime levels depend on

- number of planets recently destroyed by the Death Star (more planets destroyed -> less crime)

And so on….
